The parameter file formats for mdSim and mcSim simulations are similar in many respects, and so will be discussed together.  

\section user_param_pc_section Example
An example of a parameter file for pscf_pc3D is shown below. 

\code
System{
  Mixture{
    nMonomer  2
    monomers  0   A   1.0  
              1   B   1.0 
    nPolymer  1
    Polymer{
      nBlock  2
      nVertex 3
      blocks  0  0  0  1  0.25
              1  1  1  2  0.75
      phi     1.0
    }
    ds   0.01
  }
  ChiInteraction{
    chi  0   0   0.0
         1   0   20.0
         1   1   0.0
  }
  unitCell  cubic   1.9254998725
  mesh              10  10  10
  groupName         I_m_-3_m
  AmIterator{
    maxItr   100
    epsilon  1e-10
    maxHist  50
    domain   1
  }
}
\endcode


\section user_param_pc_overview_section File Structure

The structure of a pscf_pcNd parameter file is shown below in skeleton 
form below.
\code
System{
  Mixture{
     ...
  }
  ChiInteraction{
     ...
  }
  unitCell ...
  mesh ....
  groupName ...
  AmIterator{
     ...
  }
}
\endcode
The purpose of each subblock and parameter in the main System block
is as follows:
<ul>
<li>
Mixture: Description of molecular species and composition of the mixture. 
</li>
<li>
ChiInteraction: Values of Flory-Huggins (chi) interaction parameters
</li>
<li> unitCell: Description of periodic unit cell </li>
<li> mesh: Description of mesh used for spatial discretization </li>
<li> groupName: Name of the crystallographic space group </li>
<li> 
AmIterator: parameters required by the iterator
</li>
<ul>

The Mixture and ChiInteration subblocks are identical to those used in
the pscf_fd program, and so are not described separately below.

\section user_param_pc_AmIterator_section AmIterator Block

The AmIterator block provides parameters required by the Anderson-Mixing 
(AM) iterator that is used to solve the nonlinear self-consistent field 
(SCFT) equations. 

The value of the epsilon parameter gives the desired tolerance in the 
solution of the SCFT equations. The iterative loop exits when the 
maximum error drops below epsilon.

The domain parameter is a boolean variable that can be used to enable
or disable optimization of the unit cell. Setting domain = 0 gives a
rigid unit cell with the dimensions given by the unitCell parameter.
Setting domain = 1 instructs the program to adjust the unit cell
parameters so as to minimize the free energy.

